Description: Limestone figure of a woman during child-birth. Simple triangular votive plaque with a roughly carved naked pregnant woman. Also known as a ‘baubo’ figure. Carved from soft limestone.
Findspot: Found/Acquired: Great Temenos, Vicinity (outside) of the north-west corner (Hogarth excavations 1903), in 6th century deposit
Curator's comments: Object owned and held by Egyptian Museum, Cairo. This record is included in the British Museum database as part of the Museum’s Naukratis Project, a research collaboration that aims to virtually re-unite finds from the ancient port city of Naukratis, now distributed over 80 museums worldwide.

This piece was excavated by Hogarth at the northwest corner of the Great Temenos (most likely outside), in a '6th century' deposit (Hogarth et. al. 1905, 129). These child-birth plaques were common in Naukratis (Petrie 1886, 40, pl.19.4; Gutch in Hogarth 1899, 82, see notes for nos. 49-56; Hogarth 1905, 127-9, Fig. 8a; British Museum 1965,0930.954; Cairo TR20/9/27/25) and attributed to Naukratis (Cambridge E.SU.146). Such figure plaques were discovered by Hogarth in the northwest corner of the Great Temenos, in '6th century' deposits and were also ‘common’ in 6th century deposits around the town (Edgar in Gutch et al. 1905, 128-129, pl.8a). Petrie dated them to the 6th and 4th century BC (Petrie 1886, 40, pl.19.4). Parallels are known from Kom el Zalat, near Damenhur (Cairo SR5/6442), Memphis (Petrie Museum UC38346) and acquired in Alexandria (Cairo SR5/6490).
Bibliographic references: Hogarth, Lorimer & Edgar 1905 / Naukratis 1903 (, p. 128-9, fig. 8a)
